d on to Southeast Asia, colonial police forces struggled with the unrest and conflict that stemmed from Britain’s withdrawal from its empire. As the shadow of decolonisation grew ever longer, so colonial police forces reverted back to their traditional role as a colony’s first line of defence. At the same time, as tensions increased throughout the empire, so too did the power of the police through the development of police intelligence systems and counter-insurgency units. Colonial policing and the imperial endgame controversially asserts that it was coercion rather than consent which was more commonly associated with the work of police forces during this period of political dislocation.Georgina Sinclair's focussed study of colonial policing during this period facilitates a greater understanding of the processes of decolonisation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDecolonizationzGreat Britain. 0aPolicezGreat BritainxColoniesxHistoryy20th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAustralia.  aBritish Caribbean.  aBritish Colonial Africa.  aBritish North America Act.  aBritish law.  aCanada.  aColonial Police Service.  aIrish-colonial policing models.  aKenya.  aMiddle East.  aSierra Leone Police.  aSouth Africa.  acolonial conflict.  acolonial police forces.  acrime-fighting.  adecolonisation.  aimperial police forces.  ametropolitan-English policing models.  apost-war reform.  apostcolonial state.1 aSinclair, Georgina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779391140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847793911423Coveruhttps://www.degruy